Subject:    The true spirit of the domain system
From:       <a href="?a=95837661700001&r=1&w=2">Peter Karp &lt;KARP () SUMEX-AIM ! ARPA&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198611">1986-11-26 12:25:46</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026827&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026827&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

As I understand it, the root servers don't have entries for *.BITNET and
*.CSNET because this is *NOT* in the true spirit of the domain system.
Domains are supposed to apply to organizations like Universities and
corporations, not network topologies, which are much more likely to
change.  Names of the form X.CSNET are a hack which should eventually go
away.  If we have a University called UFOO which is connected to CSNet,
the proper approach is to create a domain called UFOO.EDU , and create
MX entries which forward *.UFOO.EDU to CSNet-Relay.  Yes?

This, anyway, is a strict interpretation of the existing system.  Whether
this is actually going to be done for BITNET sites as well I don't know.
That is, the above looks good in principle, but whether people are 
actually going to sit down and register every organization with a
BITNET host in the domain tables, I don't know.

Peter
